<TITLE> Poland reiterates vow to reopen EU treaty debate </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WARSAW, July 5 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - President Lech Kaczynski reiterated on Thursday that Poland plans to reopen discussion on the voting system in a new European Union treaty, a position that has drawn the anger of partners in the bloc. Poland says it won an unwritten concession on the treaty at a summit last month to ensure that countries just short of the votes needed to block an EU decision could delay it for up to two years. EU leaders say the deal was only to allow a delay for a maximum of about four months, and they have warned Poland not to try to bring the issue up again when EU governments meet later this month. "At this moment we don't have either two years or three months written down," Kaczynski said in an interview for public television on Thursday. "This issue should be discussed at the Intergovernmental Conference." Poland says it won the concession, as well as a 10-year postponement of the start of the new voting system, for dropping its earlier threat to veto the treaty entirely because it said the vote mechanism gave too much power to big states. The president's twin brother, Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski, was quoted by the German daily Die Welt as saying that Poland had a "gentleman's agreement" on the two year delay it demands. He said German Chancellor Angela Merkel, who had pushed hard for the treaty while Germany held the EU presidency, had herself been aware of what was discussed. "Verbal agreements are valid in civil law," he said. "There was a political agreement, a gentlemen's agreement, and as such it must be respect
